The Kiden Star

In Zone 5 of Bidi Bidi, we came across a group of ladies near one of the water wells we‚Äôve drilled in the area. A woman named Mary was handcrafting these beautifully intricate creations. Each one takes over one week to make and they‚Äôre meant to hang in the home as a symbol of hope.

Like many villages in Bidi Bidi, Mary‚Äôs is comprised of primarily women and children who‚Äôve suffered unimaginable amounts of trauma. Mary began creating her designs as a way to bring the women together; to get them out of their homes and move past their pain.

The Kiden Star
-
In Zone 5 of Bidi Bidi, I came across a group of ladies near one of the water wells we‚Äôve recently drilled in the area. A woman named Mary was handcrafting these beautifully intricate creations that she designed. Each one takes over one week to make and they‚Äôre meant to hang in the home as a symbol of hope.
-
Like many villages in Bidi Bidi, Mary‚Äôs is comprised of primarily women and children who‚Äôve suffered unimaginable amounts of trauma. Mary began creating her designs as a way to bring the women together; to get them out of their homes and move past their pain.
-
We are committed to helping Mary and her team start up a small workshop to help enhance and expand their handicraft initiative as a means of improving their own lives. I asked Mary what she calls them and she replied shyly that they have no name.
- 
Abednego asked for her last name and she whispered, ‚ÄúKiden.‚Äù We suggested the Kiden Flower. ‚ÄúNo,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúI like Kiden Star.‚Äù
-
And that she was.
-
#refugee #bidibidirefugeesettlement #uganda #livelihood

[{'node': {'text': "After embarking on a seemlingly impossible journey, Treana and the Obakki Foundation team (finally!) found the women who designed the Bidi Bidi scarf. Treana was dedicated to keeping her word and supporting economic initiatives for this incredible group of women. Read her story below. - 
The Reunion
-
It seemed like an impossible task: search the entire resettlement area for 15 women in a population of over 280,000. After speaking to a number of people we ended up in the spot where we‚Äôd first met the women two years earlier. This is where they painted and sang and began to heal from the trauma of their journey to Bidi Bidi. Their paintings inspired the design of our Bidi Bidi scarf and I was back to show them the results of their efforts.
-
We showed everyone we encountered pictures from our last visit until someone recognized the ladies. Within minutes they were running to greet us with tears, hugs and disbelief that we had returned when so many others had not.
- 
We signed their guest book (which usually happens after you‚Äôve spent time together) and Abednego noticed we were the last ones to sign it, in 2017, which was heartbreaking. Since we‚Äôd last met, seven other NGOs had dropped by with livelihood programs for the women and they had one sewing machine to show for it, with no instructions on how to use it.
- 
When the ladies heard that women around the world were wearing their designs, they cried - after false starts and broken promises, the women of Bidi Bidi were seeing that their work had meaning. These unbelievably strong and resilient women had only asked for an opportunity. As a result of it, they're now able to rebuild their own lives with purpose.
-
It was a beautiful day. Thank you to all of you around the world who are wearing this scarf in support of these beautiful women.
-
üì∑: @farahnoshphotographs -
#uganda #bidibidirefugeesettlement#refugees #obakkifoundation"}}]

[{'node': {'text': 'When we gave students of the Bidibidi refugee camp the opportunity to draw during workshops, young girls, often caretakers for younger siblings, drew pictures of homes with flowers and the lives that they hoped to live someday. Yet, they created a delicate balance between choosing different colored pencils and keeping the babies from crying, a balance of being both an imaginative child and a gentle caregiver. This is one example of providing opportunities for young women‚Äôs empowerment, to be involved in creative experiences without limitations due to their circumstances. #Artolution empowers all young women to achieve and ensures that their voices are part of the ongoing dialogue and storytelling of our global community.  With @maxfrieder @unhcruganda @refugees @windleuganda @chimeforchange #artolution #bidibidirefugeesettlement #bidibidirefugeecamp #uganda #refugees #refugeeswelcome #withrefugees #standwithrefugees #unhcruganda #windleuganda #southsudanese #coexistance #southsudan #refugeeart #chimeforchange #gucci #balanceforbetter #internationalwomensday #iwd2019 #iwd #womenshistorymonth'}}]

[{'node': {'text': 'The story of a dream of a little boy who grew up with his mother, a water carrier in the Bidibidi refugee camp in Uganda on the border of South Sudan. He dreamed to become a doctor, to take care of his family, and when he grew up, he healed ALL of the children. These are the dreams of the children of the Bidibidi refugee camp. It is their belief and expression through art that if animals can all live in harmony, then so can the humans. Painted and inspired by hundreds of South Sudanese Refugees and local Ugandan and South Sudanese Artists, the newest Artolution Artist team. With @maxfrieder @unhcruganda @refugees @windleuganda #artolution #bidibidirefugeesettlement #bidibidirefugeecamp #uganda #refugees #refugeeswelcome #withrefugees #standwithrefugees #unhcruganda #windleuganda#southsudanese #coexistance #southsudan #refugeeart'}}]

[{'node': {'text': 'The children of the Bidibidi refugee camp chose to tell the story of coexistence. Tribes from all across South Sudan represented here, all with their own stories of displacement. The images of two faces are filled with the people of the different communities with arrows to demonstrate speaking and listening to one another. The children remind us that the different tribes of South Sudan and the world have the capacity to understand through the quiet of listening. Community integration exemplified in one small community impacted by the Global Refugee Crisis. With @maxfrieder @unhcruganda @refugees educationaboveall_eaa @windleuganda #artolution #bidibidirefugeesettlement #bidibidirefugeecamp #uganda #refugees #refugeeswelcome #withrefugees #standwithrefugees #unhcruganda #windleuganda#southsudanese #coexistance #southsudan #refugeeart'}}]

[{'node': {'text': 'Originally, Bidi Bidi was expected to hold only 40,000 inhabitants. At one point, 3,000 people arrived daily, having walked hundreds of miles to escape the tragedy left behind in South Sudan. Now, it‚Äôs a sprawling expanse of mud-walled huts and tents, inhabited by almost 300,000 people who have fled violence & famine.
-
The registration process is arduous and daunting - and on this long journey for a new life, it‚Äôs only the beginning.
-
Check out our IG stories to learn more about the arrival process into one of the world‚Äôs largest refugee camps.
-
#bidibidirefugeesettlement #uganda #southsudan #refugee #philanthropic #cleanwater #charity
-
üì∑: @farahnoshphotographs'}}]

[{'node': {'text': 'Children play as a storm brews over the largest refugee camp in the world, Bidibidi in northern Uganda.

Even though Bidibidi refugee camp has now become home to over 285,000 people, refugees from South Sudan are still arriving at Uganda‚Äôs border, mostly on foot, tired and hungry, carrying children and a few household goods.

Near Bidi Bidi is another camp, Palorinya, which is Uganda‚Äôs second largest refugee camp with 165,000 refugees. At this camp rations are inadequate to meet household needs, leaving refugees, particularly children and the elderly, facing malnutrition.

Caritas has launched an emergency appeal for South Sudanese refugees in Uganda to improve the lives of people in the Palorinya camp in the same way that we helped in Bidi Bidi.

#Caritas #Hope #Children #HopeForChildren #SouthSudan #Uganda #BidiBidi #bidibidirefugeesettlement #ProtectChildren #SDGs #Africa

Photo by @tommy.trenchard for Caritas'}}]

[{'node': {'text': 'The story of a dream of a little boy who grew up with his mother as a water carrier in the Bidibidi refugee camp on the border of South Sudan. He dreamed to become a doctor, to take of his family, and to take care of all of the children. [{'node': {'text': 'Admiration i have for this lady ‚ù§

#Repost @obakkifoundation
‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢
Hi, Treana Peake here checking in. -
Gardens & Bedsheets
-
It started with a garden - a sad little sprinkling of seeds on unforgiving dirt - that had no business being there. We were at our last borehole inspection of the day, and as we arrived, Abedengo walked right past me to a tiny crop of struggling plants off in the distance.
-
The garden was likely not going to make it, but that wasn‚Äôt the point - this meagre little plot was proof of someone‚Äôs determination and ingenuity. In our work, we often come across forward-thinking people - and it is people like this that we build our programs around! The person behind this garden was a visionary thinker dedicated to changing the current situation, so we went looking for whoever was responsible.
-
This is how we met Morris.
- 
The Bidi Bidi resettlement is spread out over a massive area made up of many where most of the women are severely traumatized from their experiences in the war. Morris told us that the women were staying in their tukuls (homes) so a couple of them pooled their money to form a co-op for the women. Whether it was gardening, crafts or sewing bedsheets, the co-op gave the women purpose and helped them process their trauma.
-
Today the stars aligned. In the middle of nowhere I found a collective of sewers with a business plan, goals and so much ambition! I can‚Äôt wait to tell you about all of the plans we made together.
- 
I still get shivers when I consider the chances that we met Morris that day - all because Abedengo saw a garden that was planted near our borehole. The thing that ultimately brought us together on that day was water. It always begins with water.
-
#uganda #bidibidirefugeesettlement#refugees #waterwell #obakkifoundation'}}]

[{'node': {'text': 'A note from our founder. -
Bee Teacher
-
We had 25 spots for our beekeeping workshop and I was hoping to fill half of them. I partnered with Daniel, a South Ugandan bee expert with over 19 years experience, and over three days we would be teaching the basics of beekeeping.
-
When we walked into our classroom there were 40 people waiting, almost double what we were expecting. Every person was really excited to learn more - my teaching career had officially begun, whether I was ready or not.
-
Some of our students were walking four kilometres each way every day to attend our workshop and they were grateful for the opportunity. Every day I sat with each student; taking their pictures, memorizing their names, and hearing their stories. I wanted to learn their motivations to pursue beekeeping because we will be building our program around them.
-
One woman had 2 children of her own before taking in a baby she found in the forest, another left on her doorstep and a third who had been recently orphaned. She was now a single mother of five and beekeeping will feed her family. For her honey is money. Every person had a specific reason to be there and they were all very aware that the bees will change their lives.
-
üêùüêù
-
üì∑: @farahnoshphotographs -
#uganda #beekeeping #obakkifoundation#bidibidirefugeesettlement #refugees#africa'}}]

[{'node': {'text': '#Repost @treanapeake
‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢
The Peace Tree
-
Child Friendly Spaces have been set up around Bidi Bidi as a safe place for children to process their trauma through different forms of therapy, but resources in Bidi Bidi are extremely limited aside from some playground equipment that thousands of children must share.
-
Thankfully, these children have Betty and John, who‚Äôve introduced Peace Therapy. The idea is an simple as it is ingenious - leave messages of peace on the peace tree. Betty and John encourage the children to express themselves anonymously on paper and for many it‚Äôs the first step to healing.
-
The torn strips of paper are tattered, but the messages they deliver are powerful: no discrimination of children; you must respect your elders; you should not force a child to work; and - the one that brings me to tears - you should be a child of one mother and one father.
-
Leaving their messages - their pleas for peace - these kids are able to see in all of the other messages that they aren‚Äôt alone. Betty and John have undertaken an insurmountable task: teaching peace to an entire generation of children who know only war.
-
#uganda #bidibidirefugeesettlement #refugees #africa #obakkifoundation
-
üì∑/ @farahnoshphotographs'}}]

[{'node': {'text': "After embarking on a seemlingly impossible journey, Treana and the Obakki Foundation team (finally!) found the women who designed the Bidi Bidi scarf. Treana was dedicated to keeping her word and supporting economic initiatives for this incredible group of women. Read her story below. - 
The Reunion
-
It seemed like an impossible task: search the entire resettlement area for 15 women in a population of over 280,000. After speaking to a number of people we ended up in the spot where we‚Äôd first met the women two years earlier. This is where they painted and sang and began to heal from the trauma of their journey to Bidi Bidi. Their paintings inspired the design of our Bidi Bidi scarf and I was back to show them the results of their efforts.
-
We showed everyone we encountered pictures from our last visit until someone recognized the ladies. Within minutes they were running to greet us with tears, hugs and disbelief that we had returned when so many others had not.
- 
We signed their guest book (which usually happens after you‚Äôve spent time together) and Abednego noticed we were the last ones to sign it, in 2017, which was heartbreaking. Since we‚Äôd last met, seven other NGOs had dropped by with livelihood programs for the women and they had one sewing machine to show for it, with no instructions on how to use it.
- 
When the ladies heard that women around the world were wearing their designs, they cried - after false starts and broken promises, the women of Bidi Bidi were seeing that their work had meaning. These unbelievably strong and resilient women had only asked for an opportunity. As a result of it, they're now able to rebuild their own lives with purpose.
-
It was a beautiful day. Thank you to all of you around the world who are wearing this scarf in support of these beautiful women.
-
üì∑: @farahnoshphotographs -
#uganda #bidibidirefugeesettlement#refugees #obakkifoundation"}}]

[{'node': {'text': 'A message from our founder: ‚ÄúWe are on a mission to find the ladies who designed our Bidi Bidi scarf! In 2017, on a UNHCR mission, I spent time with these women - but now due to staff turnover, there isn‚Äôt anyone left here that seems to know where these women are!
-
For those of you who don‚Äôt know about this scarf, the strong women in the refugee area asked to used their own two hands to create a future for themselves. Inspired by this, I brought out paint and paper and watched them tell their story through art.
-
I took their art home, put it on scarves (see link in profile!) and sold it around the world. Today I am bringing back 100% of the net proceeds to put into livelihood initiatives to help get these women back on their feet!
-
It will be an exciting day - just have to find them first!!!‚Äù
-
#bidibidirefugeecamp #uganda#obakkifoundation#bidibidirefugeesettlement'}}]

[{'node': {'text': 'The Kiden Star is now available to shop via link in bio with 100% of net proceeds supporting Mary and other women‚Äôs economic initiatives in Bidi Bidi.
‚Ä¢
Through our founder‚Äôs eyes:
‚Ä¢
‚ÄúThe Kiden Star
-
In Zone 5 of Bidi Bidi, I came across a group of ladies near one of the water wells we‚Äôve recently drilled in the area. A woman named Mary was handcrafting these beautifully intricate creations that she designed. Each one takes over one week to make and they‚Äôre meant to hang in the home as a symbol of hope.
-
Like many villages in Bidi Bidi, Mary‚Äôs is comprised of primarily women and children who‚Äôve suffered unimaginable amounts of trauma. Mary began creating her designs as a way to bring the women together; to get them out of their homes and move past their pain.
-
We are committed to helping Mary and her team start up a small workshop to help enhance and expand their handicraft initiative as a means of improving their own lives. I asked Mary what she calls them and she replied shyly that they have no name.
- 
Abednego asked for her last name and she whispered, ‚ÄúKiden.‚Äù We suggested the Kiden Flower. ‚ÄúNo,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúI like Kiden Star.‚Äù
-
And that she was.‚Äù
-
#refugee #bidibidirefugeesettlement#uganda #livelihood
üì∑: @farahnoshphotographs'}}]

[{'node': {'text': "-
The Reunion
-
It seemed like an impossible task: search the entire resettlement area for 15 women in a population of over 280,000. After speaking to a number of people we ended up in the spot where we‚Äôd first met the women two years earlier. This is where they painted and sang and began to heal from the trauma of their journey to Bidi Bidi. Their paintings inspired the design of our Bidi Bidi scarf and I was back to show them the results of their efforts.
-
We showed everyone we encountered pictures from our last visit until someone recognized the ladies. Within minutes they were running to greet us with tears, hugs and disbelief that we had returned when so many others had not.
- 
We signed their guest book (which usually happens after you‚Äôve spent time together) and Abednego noticed we were the last ones to sign it, in 2017, which was heartbreaking. Since we‚Äôd last met, seven other NGOs had dropped by with livelihood programs for the women and they had one sewing machine to show for it, with no instructions on how to use it.
- 
When the ladies heard that women around the world were wearing their designs, they cried - after false starts and broken promises, the women of Bidi Bidi were seeing that their work had meaning. These unbelievably strong and resilient women had only asked for an opportunity. As a result of it, they're now able to rebuild their own lives with purpose.
-
It was a beautiful day. Thank you to all of you around the world who are wearing this scarf in support of these beautiful women.
-
üì∑: @farahnoshphotographs -
#uganda #bidibidirefugeesettlement #refugees #obakkifoundation"}}]

[{'node': {'text': '#Repost @treanapeake
‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢
We are on a mission to find the ladies who designed our Bidi Bidi scarf! In 2017, on a UNHCR mission, I spent time with these women - but now due to staff turnover, there isn‚Äôt anyone left here that seems to know where these women are!
-
For those of you who don‚Äôt know about this scarf, the strong women in the refugee area asked to used their own two hands to create a future for themselves. Inspired by this, I brought out paint and paper and watched them tell their story through art.
-
I took their art home, put it on scarves (see link in profile!) and sold it around the world. Today I am bringing back 100% of the net proceeds to put into livelihood initiatives to help get these women back on their feet!
-
It will be an exciting day - just have to find them first!!!
-
#bidibidirefugeecamp #uganda #obakkifoundation #bidibidirefugeesettlement'}}]

[{'node': {'text': 'Humble beginnings. I love watching rural soccer games like these wherever I go, especially when its a free for all.. meaning, no goal posts and in some cases, no ‚Äúreal‚Äù soccer balls to play with. It‚Äôs conditions like these that help create, shape & mold the next great generation of athletes. Not to mention that for most, this is the only hope they have at a better life. There‚Äôs only one language you need to speak in order to play and that language is futebol which is practically built into every kid. All you need is a ball and a target. This is what makes this sport the most popular in the world.'}}]

[{'node': {'text': 'We're proud to have a founder (@treanapeake) who is so involved with the communities that our programs support. Having been to Africa over 50 times, Treana is deeply connected to the people. Follow along as she documents her travels in Uganda the next few weeks.
-
"I can never truly describe how it feels to be back. I step off the plane and breathe in a fusion of spicy sweetness that only someone who‚Äôs been here can understand. I instantly feel grounded.
-
Having been to this part of the world over 50 times, it feels natural to be here - it feels comfortably familiar. Yet it never gets old. I‚Äôve been coming here long enough to know it‚Äôs never ‚Äòjust another trip to Africa‚Äô.
-
We are about to meet faces that we will never forget. I know that our programs will touch people‚Äôs hearts and create friendships and partnerships that we will hang onto for the rest of our lives. I know that we will see hardship around every corner but that our commitment will grow stronger.
-
I take in another deep breath and prepare for the extraordinary."

[{'node': {'text': '#Repost @treanapeake
‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢
-
Crossing the Nile
-
We arrive at the shores of the White Nile and huddled aboard an overly populated boat with a hundred newly arrived refugees from South Sudan. They‚Äôve crossed the border at Nimule after having walked for days. Once on the other side of the river, they‚Äôll travel northwest on foot to the resettlement area and register themselves as refugees.
-
There were two young men with traditional Dinka scarring waiting in the line. Their eyes were distant as they gazed into nothing. Violence has devastated their country for so long that I wondered why these men were only fleeing now. Did they stay behind to fight or was there another reason? What had they seen and experienced? Where did they find their strength to remain and what now was their breaking point?
-
I approached the men, greeting them in their dialect. I told them, ‚ÄúC√´ y√Øn b√§√§k‚Äù, which means, ‚ÄúHello‚Äù and continued to say ‚ÄúYou are welcome here‚Äù - like it was my place to say it; like it was my country they had fled to??! Sigh. I wanted them to feel like someone had noticed them. I wanted them to feel like someone cared.
-
They smiled but only for the briefest moment and then fell expressionless into line with the hundreds of others who began to board the boat.
-
#uganda #refugee #bidibidirefugeesettlement'}}]

[{'node': {'text': 'You know how a story can sometimes just grab you by the heart? That‚Äôs how I felt when I first saw @noralorek‚Äôs portrait series in @natgeo and read about these South Sudanese refugees and their Milayas. ‚ÄúWith most of the refugees being women and children who leave in the middle of the night during shootings, their bedsheets, called Milayas are often one of the only things they carry with them. The handmade patterns have been made for generations in Sudan and South Sudan and the Milaya tradition continues in what has become their  temporary home while waiting for the war to end‚Äù. I was not the only one touched by this story- hundreds of people asked @noralorek how they could help- and if they could purchase a Milaya in support of the refugees. I have been in communication with Nora in the hope of facilitating this effort- and can‚Äôt wait to hear how her recent trip to Uganda went and the talks of a future Milaya Foundation. Follow her @noralorek and read more about this amazing story!!! #milaya #nationalgeographic #noralorek #sudan #uganda #bidibidirefugeesettlement'}}]

.

"World Refugee Day is one of those global moments when we can stop and raise awareness of an issue that‚Äôs more acute than ever and also think about how we can respond and help children and families,‚Äù he says.
.
